dev.marksman.collectionviews

Interface ImmutableVector<A>

  • Type Parameters:
    A - the element type
    All Superinterfaces:
    Immutable, java.lang.Iterable<A>, java.util.RandomAccess, Vector<A>
    All Known Subinterfaces:
    ImmutableNonEmptyVector<A>

    public interface ImmutableVector<A>
extends Vector<A>, Immutable
    A Vector that is guaranteed at compile-time to safe from mutation anywhere. In other words, it owns the sole reference to the underlying collection.

    In addition to guarantees of Vector, provides the following benefits :

    • fmap(com.jnape.palatable.lambda.functions.Fn1<? super A, ? extends B>) always returns a ImmutableVector.
    • tail() always returns a ImmutableVector.
    • take(int) always returns a ImmutableVector.
    • drop(int) always returns a ImmutableVector.
    • slice(int, int) always returns a ImmutableVector.
    • toImmutable() always returns itself.

        default ImmutableVector<A> toImmutable()
        Description copied from interface: Vector
        Returns an ImmutableVector containing the same elements as this one. This method will make a copy of the underlying data structure if necessary to guarantee immutability.

        If this Vector is an ImmutableVector already, no copies are made and this method is a no-op.

        default <B> ImmutableVector<B> fmap(com.jnape.palatable.lambda.functions.Fn1<? super A,? extends B> f)
        Description copied from interface: Vector
        Maps a function over the elements in a Vector and returns a new Vector of the same size (but possibly a different type).

        Does not make any copies of underlying data structures.

        This method is stack-safe, so a Vector can be mapped as many times as the heap permits.

      • take

        default ImmutableVector<A> take(int count)
        Description copied from interface: Vector
        Returns a new Vector that contains at most the first count elements of this Vector.

        Does not make copies of any underlying data structures.

        Use caution when taking a small slice of a huge Vector, as the smaller slice will hold onto a reference of the larger one, and will prevent it from being GC'ed. To avoid this situation, use Vector.copyTakeFromIterable(int, java.lang.Iterable<A>) instead.

        Specified by:

        Description copied from interface: Vector
        Create a slice of an existing Vector.

        Does not make copies of any underlying data structures.

        Use caution when taking a small slice of a huge Vector that you no longer need, as the smaller slice will hold onto a reference of the larger one, and will prevent it from being GC'ed. To avoid this situation, use Vector.copySliceFromIterable(int, int, java.lang.Iterable<A>) instead.

        Specified by:
        slice in interface Vector<A>
        Parameters:

        endIndexExclusive - the end index (exclusive) of the slice. Must be >= startIndex. May exceed the size of the Vector, in which case the slice will contain as many elements as available.

        a Vector<A>
